answers.body_markdown:
Yes, it&#39;s perfectly fine. It&#39;s commonly used when objects are immutable. Such a method may return a copy of the object and apply some modification.

Take for example [`LocalDate.withYear`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/LocalDate.html#withYear-int-) which is an instance method which returns a new immutable `LocalDate`. Sample usage:

    LocalDate date = LocalDate.of(2018, 1, 1);
    LocalDate nextYear = date.withYear(2019);

We now have two distinct instances, one a year after the other.

It is not required that your object be immutable if you want to do this, though that might be where it&#39;s most commonly used. If your class is not immutable, you should probably note in your JavaDoc that the method returns a new instance rather than modifying the existing one in order to prevent any confusion.

---

Alternatively, another implementation that would match that signature would be to modify the current instance and then `return this`:

    class Matrix {
        Matrix flipHorizontal() {
            //do the flip...
            return this;
        }
    }

This would effectively be a kind of [fluent interface](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluent_interface). It may be desirable, but in your case I think it&#39;s probably not.

